00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:04.908
You could, if you wanted,
and I often do this,

00:04:04.908 --> 00:04:08.628
you could combine SWOT across
the top with supply--

00:04:08.628 --> 00:04:18.300
with Porter in the rows so that
if you take potential entrants,

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:21.329
threat of entry,
your strengths might be that

00:04:21.329 --> 00:04:24.430
there's no money to be made in
this field,

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:26.269
so not many people are going to
want to do it,

00:04:26.269 --> 00:04:29.665
or it might be that there are
huge switching costs so that

00:04:29.665 --> 00:04:32.170
once people have bought your
equipment,

00:04:32.170 --> 00:04:36.295
it is very difficult for them
to switch to other people's

00:04:36.295 --> 00:04:37.180
equipment.
 

00:04:37.180 --> 00:04:41.079
The weakness might be that
you're making money,

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:45.314
and that the Financial
Times just ran a large

00:04:45.314 --> 00:04:49.300
article about how lucrative your
business is,

00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:52.379
which is likely to attract the
attention of others.

00:04:52.379 --> 00:04:59.064
Opportunities;
perhaps--how is barriers to

00:04:59.064 --> 00:05:02.319
entry an opportunity?
 

00:05:02.319 --> 00:05:07.250
Perhaps you can build pricing
advantages--

00:05:07.250 --> 00:05:12.403
if you increase the scale of
your operation your unit costs

00:05:12.403 --> 00:05:17.379
may get low enough that whenever
a new entrant comes,

00:05:17.379 --> 00:05:20.990
you can crush him with low
prices.

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:28.285
Threat;
similarly, somebody else may

00:05:28.285 --> 00:05:33.283
jump in and get the higher scale
of production much lower unit

00:05:33.283 --> 00:05:35.170
costs and crush you.
 

00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:41.519
You can walk all the way
through the twenty cells there,

00:05:41.519 --> 00:05:46.240
but it--frameworks like this
are meant to be useful and when

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:48.834
they're useful they--
you use them,

00:05:48.834 --> 00:05:52.208
and if there's a particular
cell here that doesn't make any

00:05:52.208 --> 00:05:55.538
sense,
you just put an X through it

00:05:55.538 --> 00:05:56.620
and go on.
 

00:05:56.620 --> 00:06:01.387
Another concept that we've used
briefly and it gets to be

00:06:01.387 --> 00:06:06.240
important in cases like SELCO is
vertical integration,

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:10.300
which I've drawn horizontally,
as almost everyone else does.

00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:16.910
The rough idea here is that on
the left is the supply of raw

00:06:16.910 --> 00:06:21.839
materials, and then making of
the product;

00:06:21.839 --> 00:06:24.649
its assembly,
its distribution and sale all

00:06:24.649 --> 00:06:25.920
the way out here.
 

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:29.160
The sale end is called the
forward part of integration,

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:30.660
so forward integration.
 

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:34.964
The raw materials and
intermediate products is called

00:06:34.964 --> 00:06:38.774
backward integration,
and so defying all logic,

00:06:38.774 --> 00:06:42.170
backward plus forward makes
vertical.

00:06:42.170 --> 00:06:45.170
Don't ask me how that came
about.

00:06:45.170 --> 00:06:51.490
Behind that process,
which we think of in very

00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:56.889
physical terms,
is an intellectual and

00:06:56.889 --> 00:07:00.877
managerial layer,
which starts not with raw

00:07:00.877 --> 00:07:03.110
materials but with a business
plan,

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:07.026
and a product design,
and the assembly of a

00:07:07.026 --> 00:07:10.430
management team,
and the creation of channels

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:12.180
for distributing the product.
 

